THE Phuthaditjhaba Magistrates Court in the Free State postponed the case against six people, including a 19-year-old Grade 11 pupil. The group is accused of being part of mob justice in Sebokeng Village, Phuthaditjhaba, in February. The incident claimed the lives of Papi Motsapi (47), Lerato Mokoena (31) and Moeketsi Noto (31), who allegedly terrorised residents. The six suspects face three charges of murder and one of attempted murder. The unavailability of investigating officers led to the postponement of the accused’s bail application. The court cannot proceed in the absence of an investigating officer, who is expected to oppose bail. Angry Sebokeng Village residents picketed outside the court demanding the release of all suspects as they believe cops arrested the wrong people. Community leader Mapuleng Mahonko said: “Police are so heartless. They failed to do proper investigations and decided to arrest innocent people, including a 19-year-old pupil.” “Those deceased criminals were dangerous. We lodged many complains at Namahadi Police Station, but nothing happened. They were terrorising the community.”   and stealing our property in the presence of police.” The pupil’s mother told Daily Sun: “My son was badly punished during his arrest. I am depressed and devastated. I know my son is innocent I cannot stop praying for him.” Police spokesman, Warrant Officer Mmako Mophiring said the court will determine whether the suspects are guilty or not. “We cannot afford to be a lawless country where people are killed without law enforcement being in place to track down the perpetrators,” he said. . “Being arrested does not mean you are guilty. Remember our law says a person is not guilty until proven otherwise,” said Mophiring. The suspects will appear in court today, 30 May.